title: For Sale:  SA VZ Scorpion Skorpion 7.65 Browning SBR ready!!
postcontent:
Don't get stung by the scorpion!  This sweet thing is SBR ready!!

THIS IS THE REAL DEAL, DON'T CONFUSE CZECHPOINT WITH OTHER COMPANIES THAT ASSEMBLE FIREARMS FROM PARTS KITS. THIS PISTOL IS 100% MADE NEW BY CZECH SMALL ARMS.

The Sa vz. 61 Scorpion is the semi-automatic version of the legendary Sa vz. 61 submachine gun (machine pistol) designed in the late 1950´s in Czechoslovakia. The Scorpion was designed for reconnaissance units, tank crews, Special Forces, and for security forces of the Ministry of Interior. The Scorpion was developed to fulfill a specific need: a firearm that could be worn like a pistol (in a holster) and capable of full automatic fire.

The design of the vz. 61 Scorpion was unique in its time. It uses the following common operational features found on a submachine gun: an unlocked bolt, magazine inserted into the bottom of the receiver (outside of the pistol grip) and a folding stock. These common features are combined with the following characteristics not usually found in submachine guns: extraordinary small size, fires from a closed bolt, and uses a rate reducer to slow full automatic fire.

The vz. 61 Scorpion offered by CzechPoint is the semi-automatic version of the original military issued firearm - it is as close as one can get to owning the legendary Scorpion submachine gun. Except for removal of the full-auto parts and rate reducer, and three modified parts with new safety, this firearm is like those used by Military and Paramilitary units in nearly 20 countries around the world. 

As shown in the photo, the vz. 61 Scorpion finish is comprised of a blued lower receiver with a black paint upper receiver (paint cured at 300 degrees fahrenheit).

2 available!!

$600 total including tax

title: For Sale:  Collectible/Shootable/Unusual Ammo
postcontent:
I've been cleaning out another one of my ammo lockers this weekend and found the following interesting items: 

500 round display pack of 70's vintage CCI Mini-Mag 40 grain copper plated solid points. To the best of my recollection these were bought around the time I was graduating from high school which was 1977. The ammo is packed in the old orange 100 round plastic boxes with the old graphics. The ammo itself is bright, shiny and sure to fire. The cardboard counter display sleeve is in good condition but does have some minor yellowing/staining from age. $100 

(2) 50 round boxes Winchester & Western .22 Mag ammo. This dates from late 60's to early 70's. Ammo condition is excellent and boxes are good. $50 

50 round box US Ammunition Company .38 Special plastic case ammo. USAC came on the scene in the early 80's with the neat idea of plastic cased ammo that could be reloaded either by hand (the bullets snap in with finger pressure) or with a very inexpensive hand held tool they were going to sell. They did a ton of marketing initially and even sent out 6 round sample boxes to dealers around the country. However it just really never caught on and it was probably because there was no real price advantage. So they went bankrupt before they really ever got going. 

I had a relative at the time who worked on Wall Street that was part of the team who was working on taking USAC public, but alas... it never happened. However he did get a few free cases of prototype ammo in the 50 round boxes that USAC was going to use commercially. So a bunch of it ended up with me and I shot a lot of it. It was great low to medium power target and plinking ammo. Now I just found a box of it left over and I think it's probably pretty collectible now especially in the 50 round commercial box because I don't think much was produced in this configuration. Ammo is in perfect shape and box is fair. Includes an  
original advertising/instruction pamphlet that was to be packed in each 50 round box. $100 

All ammo is pick up in the Brandon area. Must be at least 21 to purchase.
